What is Computer Vision?
•Computer vision is a scientific and engineering
discipline that involves extracting and interpreting
meaning from images and videos, enabling
machines to understand and process visual data.
•It employs techniques such as pattern recognition,
machine learning, and deep learning to perform
tasks such as object detection, segmentation,
recognition, and tracking.
blog-ko.superb-ai.com
What is Computer Vision?
•Using various sensors, it is possible to digitally
represent the surrounding world. The commonly
used images and videos are not the only means.
•There are various sensors such as LiDAR, radar,
ultrasonic, infrared, etc., and the technology for
digitally representing the environment continues to
advance.
koit.co.kr, axis.com
What is Computer Vision?
•This technology finds applications in various fields including autonomous driving, medical image
analysis, security systems, robot navigation, and industrial automation.

What is Computer Vision?
•Computer vision is not the same as machine learning.
•However, they can be very useful tools for each other.
•They are complementary to each other and have a

•Maria's primary responsibility is to communicate the optimal harvest conditions for fruits to the
workers. Since this significantly impacts the price of fruits, it's a crucial task directly tied to the
company's profits. How can Maria avoid individually inspecting each fruit and giving instructions?
•John is tasked with monitoring the quality of pills manufactured by a pharmaceutical company.
Before the pills are sold, John needs to spend his day identifying pills with scratches or
contamination and separating them from the good ones. How can the process be changed to
minimize the workload on employees and reduce company expenses?
Strategies for optimizing work efficiency through cv
•We can monitor and analyze the ripeness,
size, and color of fruits in real-time using
cameras, and provide the results to the
workers.
•We can capture images of normal and
abnormal pills and use image analysis to
identify scratches or contamination, allowing
for their removal.
